Link to the trailer here: &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ewh0lBcEb2U&quot; style=&quot;color:#0563c1; text-decoration:underline&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ewh0lBcEb2U&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Description/Review&lt;/b&gt;: Matteo Garrone&amp;rsquo;s DOGMAN leaves you feeling like you&amp;#39;ve just enjoyed a superb Italian opera, or an engrossing character study for a Martin Scorsese film. Or perhaps an allegorical tale from a small isolated town in a Sergio Leone spaghetti western. DOGMAN is filled with drama, pathos, and a bit of comedy, and centers on a fascinating protagonist who undergoes a dramatic change in the face of violent forces beyond his control. This wonderful character study is actually loosely based on a true story about a dog coiffeur. The main character, Marcello, is a small man with a big heart. He loves his job grooming dogs (ergo the name of his business&amp;hellip; &amp;ldquo;Dogman&amp;rdquo;) and styling winners in dog competitions. He can calm vicious dogs bigger than he, cajoling them like a dog whisperer, and will sometimes share his food with them. At one point he even risks his life and liberty to save a dog someone else has put in harms&amp;rsquo; way. Divorced, Marcello lives alone but is not lonely. He fills his days with visitations and vacations with his adoring young daughter, and meals and football games with the other businessmen in his small, run down and isolated seaside suburb on the brink of desertion. Overall, Marcello is a slight, affable man who seems to love life, and who gets along by going along. &amp;nbsp;Even so, life is not easy. Marcello and the small community are terrorized by Simone, a huge brute of a violent bully who rides a noisy motorcycle, wears a leather jacket with &amp;ldquo;Uncle Sam&amp;rdquo; emblazoned on the back, and who intimidates Marcello into providing him with cocaine and assistance in his crimes. Marcello is not a fighter, and he placates and acquiesces to Simone&amp;rsquo;s demands, trying to cajole him the way he manages the large aggressive dogs under his care. &amp;nbsp;It is the audiences&amp;rsquo; recognition that this tenuous d&amp;eacute;tente will not last that fuels the film with an sense of operatic drama; as Simone grows more and more out of control, something will have to give, probably at great cost to Marcello and those for whom he cares. DOGMAN was directed by the imaginative Italian director Matteo Garrone&amp;mdash;his TALE OF TALES is an all-time favorite adult fairy tale&amp;mdash;gorgeous and otherworldly, dark and bizarre, quirky and allegorical. His other features, GOMORRAH and REALITY, are also acclaimed award winners. Although not nominated, DOGMAN was selected as the Italian entry for the Best Foreign Language Film at the 91st Academy Awards. That means it stood in fabulous company, as many of last year&amp;rsquo;s nominees (CAPERNAUM, COLD WAR, ROMA, and SHOPLIFTERS), were all amazing films. DOGMAN has already garnered a wide range of awards, including the well-earned Best Actor Award at the 2018 Cannes International Film Festival&amp;hellip;you will not soon forget Marcello Fonte&amp;rsquo;s expressive and impressive portrayal of Marcello.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

