&lt;b&gt;Description&lt;/b&gt;: &amp;nbsp;Little Woods is a modern-day western which follows Ollie (Thor: Ragnarok&amp;lsquo;s Tessa Thompson) and Deb (Baby Driver&amp;lsquo;s Lily James), a pair of estranged sisters, both who have been living at the fringes of society in a small North Dakota town. &amp;nbsp;Ollie, who&amp;rsquo;s been illegally running pills across the Canadian border before being caught by the authorities, is looking to put the past behind her. But when her mother dies and Deb is faced with an unplanned pregnancy, Ollie must decide whether or not to return to her former way of life to prevent the foreclosure of their family home. &amp;nbsp;Nia DaCosta (who was selected to helm the upcoming Jordan Peele-produced Candyman reboot) directs this taut thriller, ripe with social commentary on the opioid crisis and the economy, where family ties are tested and the painful past resurfaces. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;DaCosta deftly balances Ollie&amp;rsquo;s illicit activities with the economic anxieties so many have to struggle with to create the kind of suspense Hitchcock or Scorsese would envy.&amp;rdquo; &amp;mdash; Andrea Thompson, Cultured Vultures. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;The life-on-the-margins drama makes a fine, tense vehicle for Tessa Thompson, who in the last few years has stood out in a variety of genres.&amp;rdquo; &amp;mdash; John DeFore, Hollywood Reporter. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;DaCosta&amp;rsquo;s meticulous work in laying out a socially conscious scenario in such a wildly entertaining way shines through, and for a film that strives towards new beginnings, one couldn&amp;rsquo;t be more excited about the future of this exceptional first-time writer/director.&amp;rdquo; &amp;mdash; Stephen Saito, The Moveable Fest&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

