&lt;b&gt;Description&lt;/b&gt;: &amp;nbsp;From A24 (Hereditary, The Witch) and director/co-writer Lee Cronin comes a terrifying new vision from Ireland! &amp;nbsp;Sarah (Se&amp;aacute;na Kerslake) and her young son Chris (James Quinn Markey) move to a new home in the Irish countryside, next to a forest that hides an enormous sinkhole. After Chris inexplicably vanishes one night, Sarah is relieved when he returns seemingly unharmed &amp;mdash; but as his behavior grows increasingly disturbing, Sarah begins to fear that the boy who has returned may not be her son at all. A new independent release that is already garnering favoring comparisons to Jennifer Kent&amp;rsquo;s masterful The Babadook, The Hole in the Ground is a chilling feature film debut from a new name to watch in horror cinema. &amp;ldquo;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Segoe UI Symbol&amp;quot;,sans-serif&quot;&gt;★★★★&lt;/span&gt;. The Hole in the Ground could very well be Ireland&amp;rsquo;s answer to The Babadook. &amp;nbsp;This changeling tale will leave you chilled.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; Kat Hughes, The Hollywood News. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Segoe UI Symbol&amp;quot;,sans-serif&quot;&gt;★★★★&lt;/span&gt;. A film operating at a suspenseful, spider-like creep that allows it to skirt your defenses and get some distance under the skin.&amp;rdquo;&amp;ndash; Mike McCahill, Guardian. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;Don&amp;rsquo;t be surprised if weeks after you see this it gropes its way into your dreams.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; Charlotte O&amp;rsquo;Sullivan, London Evening Standard.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

