&lt;b&gt;Description&lt;/b&gt;: &amp;nbsp;Another Critically Acclaimed Film at the Art Theater in Long Beach&amp;hellip;&amp;hellip;.THE FAVOURITE! &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;A fantastic little cupcake of a movie laced with thistle frosting.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp;Time Magazine. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s a perfectly cut diamond of a movie &amp;ndash; a finely executed, coldly entertaining entry in the genre of savage misanthropic baroque costume drama.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; Variety. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s a period piece with a wink. It&amp;rsquo;s also funny as hell and a true big-screen treat.&amp;rdquo; &amp;nbsp;&amp;ndash; Chicago Sun-Times. &amp;nbsp;Early 18th century. England is at war with the French. Nevertheless, duck racing and pineapple eating are thriving. A frail Queen Anne (Olivia Colman) occupies the throne and her close friend Lady Sarah Churchill (Rachel Weisz) governs the country in her stead while tending to Anne&amp;rsquo;s ill health and mercurial temper. When a new servant Abigail Masham (Emma Stone) arrives, her charm endears her to Sarah. Sarah takes Abigail under her wing and Abigail sees a chance at a return to her aristocratic roots. As the politics of war become quite time consuming for Sarah, Abigail steps into the breach to fill in as the Queen&amp;rsquo;s companion. Their burgeoning friendship gives her a chance to fulfill her ambitions and she will not let woman, man, politics or rabbit stand in her way.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

