Enjoy trailers from the AIFF&amp;rsquo;s films at their YouTube page: &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCEDttZKABte00e0hdcuPbGQ&quot; style=&quot;color:blue; text-decoration:underline&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCEDttZKABte00e0hdcuPbGQ&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;b&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12.0pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Times New Roman&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;Description&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Times New Roman&amp;quot;,serif&quot;&gt;: &amp;nbsp;Your Long Wait is Almost Over&amp;hellip;.The Amazing The 21st ANNUAL ARPA INTERNATIONAL FILM FESTIVAL, 2018, takes place Fri., Sat., and Sun. November 2-4, at the most elegant Egyptian Theater in Hollywood!!! &amp;nbsp;The AIFF 2018 is one of the premier film festivals in Hollywood, showcasing inspiring films from around the world! &amp;nbsp;This year&amp;rsquo;s lineup includes 46 films from 17 countries, including wonderful narrative features, fascinating documentaries, and riviting shorts, all exploring a diverse range of themes. Here&amp;rsquo;s a glimpse of the schedule (check out the full schedule at http://www.arpafilmfestival.com/day-by-day-schedule-and-program-at-2018-arpa-iff/ ):&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;b&gt;FRIDAY, 11/2&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
-A special Red Carpet Reception (6PM) and screening (8PM) of MONDAY NIGHTS AT SEVEN, a love story about a single father who is struggling unsuccessfully to let go of his past. The film stars Edward James Olmos, Marty Sader, past Arpa IFF award recipient Mary Apick and mixed martial arts legend Anderson Silva. A special ceremony honoring Edward James Olmos with a Lifetime Achievement Award will follow the screening of the film. Olmos, currently starring in the television series Mayans M.C., has played iconic roles both in film and television (Blade Runner, American Me, Selena, Miami Vice, The Burning Season, Battlestar Galactica) receiving Academy Award and Golden Globe nominations for &amp;ldquo;Stand and Deliver&amp;rdquo; (1988).&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;b&gt;SATURDAY, 11/3&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
-Saturday evening&amp;rsquo;s centerpiece program and reception will showcase two amazing films &amp;ndash; YEVA, Armenia&amp;rsquo;s foreign language film Oscar submission last year, as well as DIVERTED EDEN written and directed by Prince Baghdasarian. YEVA, an Armenian-Iranian co-production, is set against the backdrop of the long-running conflict between Armenia and Azerbaijan over the territory of Nagorno-Karabakh (Artsakh). &amp;nbsp;DIVERTED EDEN, winner of the Audience Award at this year&amp;rsquo;s Sedona International Film Festival, is the story of a war hero who takes matters into his own hands after his young daughter is kidnapped, as detectives unravel the mystery surrounding the unusual crime.&lt;br /&gt;
-WOMEN IN FILM MAKING &amp;ndash; PANEL DISCUSSION&lt;br /&gt;
-THE SONG OF SWAY LAKE (feature) (USA) &amp;ndash; an intriguing family drama about a young record collector and his friend who go to his family&amp;rsquo;s lake house to claim a valuable jazz recording, upon his father&amp;rsquo;s suicide.&lt;br /&gt;
-RIVER OF GOLD (documentary) (USA) &amp;ndash; a disturbing account of the apocalyptic destruction of Peru&amp;rsquo;s Amazon rainforest in the pursuit of illegally mined gold. The acclaimed documentary is narrated by Academy Award winners Sissy Spacek and Herbie Hancock.&lt;br /&gt;
-SIX MUSICIANS AND THE CITY (documentary) (Russia) &amp;ndash; Filmmaker Tatiana Daniliyants showcases 6 amazing musicians based in Yerevan, each with their own unique story and musical genre. THE GIRL IN THE SHOW (documentary) (USA) &amp;ndash; a poignant retrospective of comediennes, exploring the ways in which women&amp;rsquo;s comedy and women&amp;rsquo;s liberation have evolved together.&lt;br /&gt;
-NOWHERE (feature) (Serbia) &amp;ndash; Serbian filmmaker Predrag Velinovic tells the story of three inseparable friends who graduate together and develop a relationship balancing on a thin line between friendship and love.&lt;br /&gt;
-MODERN AMERICAN ARTISTS (documentary) (USA) &amp;ndash; Rockstar/Guitarist Peter DiStefano of the band Porno for Pyros explores his local city of Los Angeles in search of local artists to collaborate with.&lt;br /&gt;
-BETTY: THEY SAY I&amp;rsquo;M DIFFERENT (documentary) (USA) &amp;ndash; creatively blending documentary, animation and nonfiction techniques, this movie traces the life of Funk Queen Betty Davis who arrived on the 70&amp;rsquo;s scene to break boundaries for women with her daring personality, iconic fashion and outrageous funk music.&lt;br /&gt;
-DORBEEN (short) (India)- based on the life of two street children in India and their pursuit of happiness in the little things in life that most adults are unaware of or choose to ignore.&lt;br /&gt;
-ECHO (short animation) (Serbia) &amp;ndash; a young boy spends a day with his father, whom he only occasionally sees, in nature, with the game of calling Echo.&lt;br /&gt;
-GENESIS (short animation) (Iran) &amp;ndash; a fantasy short film with a critical point of view about the situation in Syria.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;b&gt;SUNDAY, 11/4&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
- The AIFF 2018 will close with a special Awards Ceremony on Sunday, November 4 at the Egyptian Theatre, with Ed Asner, Natalie Qasabian and Sveva Alviti being honored.&lt;br /&gt;
-THE PURSUIT (short) (USA) &amp;ndash; a first generation Armenian-American single mother still struggling with her cultural identity. She tries to conform with her family&amp;rsquo;s and culture&amp;rsquo;s expectations but feels that she is stuck in the middle of the Armenian and American cultures.&lt;br /&gt;
-IN VINO (feature) (USA) &amp;ndash;Charles and Linda, extremely wealthy couple, invite their closest friends and family members to dinner. Before dinner is served Charles raises the glass for a toast to his family and falls face forward on his plate DEAD. Linda confesses that she had poisoned him and she had poisoned everyone in the room to get the money. The guests have one choice: Kill one person among them and take the blame for both murders to get the antidote or&amp;hellip; DIE in one hour.&lt;br /&gt;
-UNDER THE WALNUT TREE (short) (USA) &amp;ndash; a young boy has been displaced during the massacre of his people and his family. After wandering alone for days, he is ready to give up but fights to continue to safety.&lt;br /&gt;
-MY NEW YEAR (short) (Armenia) &amp;ndash; Based on childhood memories of the devastating 1988 Spitak earthquake in Armenia. A father, for the sake of his children, struggles to find the strength and heart to live on in the aftermath of an earthquake which leaves them homeless and grieving the loss of their mother and wife.&lt;br /&gt;
-ELVIS WALKS HOME (feature) (Albania) &amp;ndash; an illegal Albanian who used to live in London, is a part time Elvis Presley impersonator. He gets a job entertaining British peacekeeping troops in the 1999 Balkans wars.&lt;br /&gt;
-AMERICAN MIRROR &amp;ndash; INTIMATIONS OF IMMORTALITY &amp;ndash; (documentary) (USA) &amp;ndash; Oscar-winning screen icon Susan Sarandon and Armenian painter Tigran Tsitoghdzyan discuss how the apparently in conflict values of beauty and aging are perceived in our modern society dominated by social media, as he limns her portrait during a timeless sitting session.&lt;br /&gt;
-TANIEL (short) (UK) &amp;ndash; Film Noir images, prophetic verse, and narration by Sean Bean tell the story of Taniel Varoujan, one of the most majestic poets of the 20th century.&lt;br /&gt;
-SIDE BY SIDE: OUT OF A KOREAN ORPHANAGE AND INTO THE WORLD (documentary) &amp;ndash; an international journey through the personal memories and experiences of abandonment, relinquishment, orphanages, aging out, and inter-country adoption from South Korea.&lt;br /&gt;
-I PROMISED HER LIFE (short) (USA) &amp;ndash; On the day of her daughter&amp;rsquo;s funeral, a grieving Armenian-American mother defies a centuries-old ritual and tests the limits of tradition as she walks the thin line between death and afterlife.&lt;br /&gt;
-LITTLE FIEL (short doc) (USA) &amp;ndash; Artist Fiel dos Santos grew up during the 16-year-long civil war in his home country of Mozambique. The only one of his family to never have shot a gun, today he makes art out of guns to commemorate the lives lost.&lt;br /&gt;
-HOMELESS (ANTOUNI) (short) (Armenia) &amp;ndash; a nine-year old Syrian-Armenian girl discovers her father&amp;rsquo;s plans of leaving their beloved homeland.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

