&lt;b&gt;Description&lt;/b&gt;: &amp;nbsp;Mark Your Calendars&amp;hellip;You WON&amp;rdquo;T Want to Miss This!!! &amp;nbsp;Highland Park Independent Film Festival (HPIFF), the grassroots Northeast Los Angeles based celebration of the art of film, announced their program line up for the 5th annual festival edition. The HPIFF showcase includes 3 Narrative Features, 3 Documentary Features and 41 Shorts. These 47 films include both 5 World Premieres, 1 USA Premiere and 6 Los Angeles Premieres. The most premieres to date. &amp;nbsp;New in 2018 is the Film Fan Fest which will take place outside of the Highland Theater featuring music, dancing, live painting by Highland Park artists and an outreach component to engage the community and learn about what they would like to see on our screen!&lt;br /&gt;
The 5th ANNUAL HPIFF ANNOUNCES THEIR 2018 PROGRAM LINE UP: &amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:&amp;quot;Times New Roman&amp;quot;, serif&quot;&gt;Opening night is &lt;b&gt;Thursday, October 4th&lt;/b&gt; with the screening of the documentary &amp;ldquo;Mary Janes: The Women of Weed&amp;rdquo; directed by Windy Borman. The documentary follows female &amp;#39;ganjapreneurs&amp;#39;, who we call Puffragettes (as in Pot + Suffragette), as they navigate the highs and lows of the legal US cannabis industry. Red Carpet starts at 6:30 pm. &amp;nbsp;Directly before the screening, HPIFF will present the 2018 HPIFF Humanitarian Award to Josefina Lopez. Josefina L&amp;oacute;pez is best known for authoring the play and co-authoring the 2002 SUNDANCE AWARD WINNING film Real Women Have Curves. Josefina will attend to receive the 2018 Humanitarian Award.&amp;nbsp; Directly after the screening of the opening night film, there will be a question and answer with the filmmakers. The evening continues with our 2nd Annual Opening Night Gala to be held at the Ebell Club in Highland Park. A red carpet, music, food and drinks will be enjoyed by the filmmakers, sponsors and honored guests.&lt;br /&gt;
The 2018 &lt;b&gt;Friday Night Film&lt;/b&gt; is &amp;ldquo;Bullitt County&amp;rdquo;. An action/thriller set in 1977 about four friends who reunite for a bachelor party to hunt for buried Prohibition money on Kentucky&amp;#39;s Bluegrass Bourbon Trail, only to become ripped apart by greed, corruption, and murder. The film is directed by David McCracken. As a gift to the community, the thought-provoking programming leading up to the closing film will screen for FREE. The Chills and Thrills program, along with the award-winning feature film from Iran, Disappearance as well as the Highland Park homegrown, Awkward Silence will screen FREE for HPIFF&amp;#39;s community on Friday, October 5th.&lt;br /&gt;
Closing HPIFF 2018 will be the shorts program, City of Angels featuring a line up made up entirely from Los Angeles based directors. A slew ofengaging and groundbreaking short films rounds off the other 2018 HPIFF Shorts Programs. On &lt;b&gt;Saturday, October 6&lt;/b&gt;, the shorts programs LatinX Voices, Sisterhood of Cinema, and All About #HLP feature an eclectic array of themes by performers from around the globe. Two powerful documentaries also make up the jam-packed Saturday line up of films. Blissful At Zero is a World Premiere for HPIFF. The film follows the last days of Nicole Tupper and it is an inspiring, thought provoking examination of what it truly means to be alive. Tales of the American charts the rich history of the Los Angeles&amp;rsquo; Hotel American which was built for black Americans in 1905, adopted by Japanese before World War II, and taken over by artists in the 1980s.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

