&lt;b&gt;Description&lt;/b&gt;-The Laemmle Theaters present NELLY, A Fascinating Biographical Drama. A high-class prostitute by choice, Nelly Arcan&amp;rsquo;s colorful life is recreated in a multilayered and stylish mix of make-believe and memoir, revealing Nelly&amp;rsquo;s alter egos: the neurotic writer, the vulnerable lover, the call girl and the star. Directed by Anne &amp;nbsp;&amp;Eacute;mond, NELLY artfully retells the life of Nelly (with an acclaimed performance by Myl&amp;egrave;ne Mackay), an escort who became an international literary star. Nelly wrote a semi-autobiographical novel, Putain in 2001, which was nominated for both the Prix M&amp;eacute;dicis and the Prix F&amp;eacute;mina, two of France&amp;#39;s most prestigious literary awards and sold over 80,000 copies as a a critically-acclaimed bestseller. She shocked the literary world with her elegant phrasing and the lurid details of sex work. &amp;nbsp;Although little is known about the author in the English-speaking world, Nelly became one of Quebec&amp;#39;s most loved and most hated public figures, a household name in both Canada and France due to her unflinching tell-all approach to life as a sex worker, over-the-top glamour, and ability to attract media attention. &amp;nbsp;The Globe &amp;amp; Mail wrote &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;she&amp;rsquo;s one of the best writers Canada has ever produced.&amp;quot; &amp;nbsp;Despite unprecedented success, Nelly&amp;rsquo;s remarkable life ended in tragedy in 2009, four days after submitting the last edits to her fourth book. Filmmaker Anne Emond is quite a up-and-coming talent and the film lends itself to an interesting discussion on feminism. NELLY was a Toronto International Film Festival Official Selection (2016).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

