&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;PARIS, 13TH DISTRICT&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
OPENS APRIL 15, 2022, IN SELECT THEATERS AND ON DEMAND&lt;br /&gt;
Get more info at the film&amp;rsquo;s IFC website:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.ifcfilms.com/films/paris-13th-district&quot;&gt;https://www.ifcfilms.com/films/paris-13th-district&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KSRww3PRyLI&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KSRww3PRyLI&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3162787520663119&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3162787520663119&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: IFC PRESENTS&amp;hellip;Adapted from Adrian Tomine&amp;rsquo;s acclaimed graphic novel, PARIS, 13TH DISTRICT weaves a breezy tapestry of modern love stories. Beautifully realized in crisp black-and-white cinematography, the electrifying, multicultural 13th arrondissement sets the stage for a panoramic tale of four young lovers. Lucie Zhang delivers a breakout performance as free-spirited &amp;Eacute;milie, who begins a casual relationship with new roommate Camille (Makita Samba). No&amp;eacute;mie Merlant (PORTRAIT OF A LADY ON FIRE) plays wide-eyed student Nora, whose new life in Paris is complicated when she is accidentally mistaken for cam girl Amber Sweet (Jehnny Beth). Stepping away from his usual genre fare, Jacques Audiard, along with script collaborators C&amp;eacute;line Sciamma and L&amp;eacute;a Mysius, brings to life the sprawling dreams of desire and human connection in the city of love. &amp;nbsp;DIRECTED BY Jacques Audiard.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;LA MAMI&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Opens on April 7 at the Maysles Cinema in New York City, Followed by Other Cities&lt;br /&gt;
Get more info from the film&amp;rsquo;s website:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.cinematropical.com/cinema-tropical/announcing-the-us-theatrical-release-of-la-mami-opens-april-7&quot;&gt;https://www.cinematropical.com/cinema-tropical/announcing-the-us-theatrical-release-of-la-mami-opens-april-7&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OVIE6ovpS3o&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OVIE6ovpS3o&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3157897191152152&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3157897191152152&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: A Potent Exploration of Female Solidarity! &amp;nbsp;The critically-acclaimed second feature documentary by Laura Herrero Garv&amp;iacute;n, and the winner of the Cinema Tropical Award for Best Film, La Mami takes us inside the ladies&amp;rsquo; bathroom-turned-cloakroom of a legendary Mexico City nightclub, the Cabaret Barba Azul. Inside the fluorescently-lit upstairs refuge we meet Do&amp;ntilde;a Olga, known as &amp;quot;La Mami&amp;quot; to the dancers and hostesses of the discotheque below, who keeps watch over the dressing room while remaining a tough-loving confidante and vigilant protector of the girls themselves. &amp;nbsp;La Mami has worked in the cabaret world for more than 45 years: as a party girl, a waitress, and a seller of songs. Now that her body has aged, she takes care of the mythical Barba Azul Cabaret from her nightly post in the cloakroom. When newcomer Priscilla arrives, Herrero Garv&amp;iacute;n&amp;rsquo;s camera quietly observes as the other girls introduce her to the secrets of the night and La Mami takes her under her wing, offering much needed advice and comfort to combat the crude machismo that surrounds them. In their world, La Mami warns, &amp;quot;men are only good for two things: for nothing, and for money.&amp;quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;COW&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
OPENS APRIL 8, 2022 IN SELECT THEATERS AND ON DEMAND&lt;br /&gt;
Screening at the Laemmle Theaters:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.laemmle.com/film/cow&quot;&gt;https://www.laemmle.com/film/cow&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Get more info at :&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.ifcfilms.com/films/cow&quot;&gt;https://www.ifcfilms.com/films/cow&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cOghmGzdjwY&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cOghmGzdjwY&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3157158734559331&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3157158734559331&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: An award winning IFC Films Release! Made over a six-year period, Andrea Arnold&amp;rsquo;s first feature-length documentary immerses us in the days and nights of Luma, a dairy cow. When Luma gives birth, she seems the happiest she can be. But Luma&amp;rsquo;s devastated when separated from her calf&amp;mdash;she seems to be looking for her lost child for the rest of the film. Her next impregnation is shorter than a one-night stand. The human beings monitoring and milking Luma, and leading her to graze, are seen on the edge of the frame, their voices a constant off-screen chorus of mainly affectionate, yet insistently controlling, encouragement. Through Arnold&amp;rsquo;s dispassionate perspective, we might imagine Luma as noble and dignified. Yet, we also might wonder about the state of her soul. A sensuous and heartbreakingly beautiful film, COW provokes a conversation about the emotional lives of animals. Directed by Andrea Arnold (AMERICAN HONEY, FISH TANK, RED ROAD)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;MUBI PRESENTS: THREE SHORTS BY OSCAR-WINNER ANDREA ARNOLD&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Ahead of the release of her forthcoming documentary Cow (opening April 8), three of Andrea Arnold&amp;#39;s breathtaking shorts are presented on the MUBI screening service:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://mubi.com/&quot;&gt;https://mubi.com/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
WASP- April 4. &amp;nbsp;A poor single mother of four must figure out what to do with her children after the guy she fancies asks her on a date, determined not to let them become an obstacle in her pursuit of a relationship. Winner: Best Live Action Short Film at the 2005 Academy Awards.&lt;br /&gt;
MILK- April 13. &amp;nbsp;Following a miscarriage, Hetty decides not to attend the funeral for her child, despite her husband&amp;rsquo;s pleading. After wandering around town, she meets Martin, and together they embark on an impulsive, drunken joyride.&lt;br /&gt;
DOG- April 2. &amp;nbsp;A teenage girl gets ready to go out to meet her boyfriend, despite her mother&amp;rsquo;s disapproval of how she&amp;rsquo;s dressed. She heads out to a deserted area with him and they have sex. However, an encounter with a stray dog reveals the true nature of her partner.&lt;/p&gt;

