&lt;p&gt;A THRILLING CINEMA TROPICAL AND FILM AT LINCOLN CENTER ANNOUNCEMENT!&lt;br /&gt;
THE 7TH ANNUAL NEIGHBORING SCENES FESTIVAL&lt;br /&gt;
The annual wide-ranging showcase of contemporary Latin American cinema featuring established auteurs as well as fresh talent from the international festival scene!&lt;br /&gt;
Discover the complete lineup, as well as the details on how to enjoy the festival,&amp;nbsp;here: &amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.filmlinc.org/daily/neighboring-scenes-returns-to-theaters-february-24-28/&quot;&gt;https://www.filmlinc.org/daily/neighboring-scenes-returns-to-theaters-february-24-28/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
February 24&amp;mdash;28 at Film at Lincoln Center; All screenings will take place in the Walter Reade Theater (165 W. 65th St.) unless otherwise noted.&lt;br /&gt;
Tickets will go on sale on February 11 at noon with discounts for students, seniors (62+), persons with disabilities, and Cinema Tropical subscribers and Film at Lincoln Center members. &amp;nbsp;Discounted All-Access Passes also available: &amp;nbsp;learn more at&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.filmlinc.org/&quot;&gt;https://www.filmlinc.org/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: The festival includes one international premiere, seven North American premieres, and six U.S. premieres! &amp;nbsp;The selections in this year&amp;#39;s slate of premieres exhibit the expansive styles, techniques, and approaches of Latin American filmmakers today, representing a wide variety of countries including Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Costa Rica, Colombia, Mexico, Peru, Uruguay, and Venezuela.&lt;br /&gt;
--Opening Night: THE OTHER TOM / EL OTRO TOM&amp;nbsp;(Rodrigo Pl&amp;aacute; and Laura Santullo). &amp;nbsp;A working-class single mom risks losing custody of her nine-year-old son, diagnosed with ADHD when she refuses to continue medicating him. &amp;nbsp;Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JTyAqZxa5G0;&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JTyAqZxa5G0;&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3129275714014300&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3129275714014300&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
--Centerpiece: THE BOX / LA CAJA&amp;nbsp;(Lorenzo Vigas.)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;A complex psychological thriller offering a critical look at Mexico&amp;rsquo;s maquiladora system. &amp;nbsp;A teenager from Mexico City travels to the north to collect the remains of his estranged father, who died under unknown circumstances. Enjoy the trailer here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4H0zOrnrfF8&lt;br /&gt;
--Two Cannes 2021 Directors&amp;#39; Fortnight selections to be presented are The Employer and the Employee, writer-director Manolo Nieto&amp;#39;s provocative Brazilian border-set drama starring Nahuel P&amp;eacute;rez Biscayart [BPM (Beats Per Minute)]; and Medusa, Anita Rocha da Silveira&amp;#39;s visionary follow-up to Kill Me Please, a reinterpretation of the mythological Greek figure of the title in a misogynistic, Bolsonarist Brazil. Additional notable presentations include Aurora, director Paz F&amp;aacute;brega&amp;#39;s delicate drama on motherhood and maternity; and Red Star, Sof&amp;iacute;a Bordenave&amp;#39;s film essay revisiting the locations where the Russian Revolution occurred 100 years earlier.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A VANISHING FOG&lt;br /&gt;
North American Premiere at the SXSW Film Festival, In Person and Online, March 11 to 19, 2022.&lt;br /&gt;
Get info and screening tix here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://schedule.sxsw.com/2022/films/2053946&quot;&gt;https://schedule.sxsw.com/2022/films/2053946&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DEmvV7vV1B0&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DEmvV7vV1B0&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3140921419516396&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3140921419516396&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: Cinema Tropical presents a North American Premiere of an Evocative and Audacious film. &amp;nbsp;A visually-exquisite social parable, with echoes of Bu&amp;ntilde;uel and Jodorowsky, and the first feature film to be shot in the mysterious and formidable P&amp;aacute;ramo of Sumapaz&amp;mdash;the largest swath of alpine moorland in the world&amp;mdash;A Vanishing Fog draws on longstanding Latin American traditions of cinematic surrealism and innovative applications of science fiction to tell the story of F, a solitary explorer and guardian of the mountains, condemned by his fate, who strives to protect the mystical and fragile ecosystem he inhabits while caring for his ailing father. &amp;nbsp;A Vanishing Fog invites audiences to immerse in a sensorial experience of images and sounds that come together to comment on Colombia&amp;rsquo;s pained histories of human and environmental rights abuses with bold cinematic precision, sensitivity, and innovation. A deeply personal film, perhaps a song or a poem caught between past and future, sanity and delirium, or bliss and tragedy, A Vanishing Fog marks Sandino as an emerging filmmaker to watch on the international festival circuit masterfully mixing sci-fi, arthouse, and genre cinematic elements.&lt;/p&gt;

