Description: &amp;nbsp;First Run Features presents Charles Frank&amp;#39;s Award-Winning Documentary. Heralded as &amp;quot;a celebration of life like you&amp;#39;ve never seen,&amp;quot; the film is a stirring, lyrical journey beneath the brusque, reticent surface of a New England fishing community. &amp;nbsp;Twenty years after a beloved local fisherman, Richie Madeiras, goes missing off the shores of Martha&amp;#39;s Vineyard, a distant cousin locates Richie&amp;#39;s kind, indelible spirit in the stories of family, friends, and the sweeping sea which has defined their lives. &amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;Told with the reverence and grace of Terrence Malick&amp;rsquo;s Tree of Life.&amp;quot;-Graffiti with Punctuation. &amp;nbsp;Named a &amp;quot;Best Documentary of 2021&amp;quot; by Video Librarian! &amp;quot;A celebration of life like you&amp;rsquo;ve never seen.&amp;quot;-Screentology&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;ROYALTY FREE: THE MUSIC OF KEVIN MACLEOD&lt;br /&gt;
The streaming &amp;amp; DVD premiere begins March 29, 2022.&lt;br /&gt;
Get more info from the films website:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://royaltyfreedoc.com/about.html&quot;&gt;https://royaltyfreedoc.com/about.html&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xPAsEervC9M&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xPAsEervC9M&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3110145569260648&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3110145569260648&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: FIRST RUN PRESENTS RYAN CAMARDA&amp;#39;S NEW FASCINATING DOCUMENTARY! &amp;nbsp;Royalty Free tells the story of the internet legend whose music has become the soundtrack of the digital world. Composer Kevin MacLeod released thousands of his songs for free and unwittingly became one of the most heard composers in the world, with his work ending up in millions of videos, thousands of films, and more than a few odd places &amp;ndash; such as theme parks and rocket launches. By releasing his music royalty free, anyone can use his music in their productions, from Martin Scorsese&amp;rsquo;s Hugo to cat videos on YouTube.The film also delves into the digital audio revolution, where one person with a synthesizer can become an entire orchestra. This democratization of music has enabled great creativity, but has also threatened the livelihood of analog musicians, from recording artists to orchestras and Broadway musicians.Ultimately, Royalty Free is about the value we as a society place on creative work, and how the evolving technological landscape influences our consumption, production, and distribution of the work itself.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;THE OLIVE TREES OF JUSTICE&lt;br /&gt;
The film&amp;rsquo;s 60th anniversary re-release will play at the historic Los Feliz 3 Theater, in Cinema 1 programmed by the American Cinematheque, with screenings on Sunday, February 6th and Saturday, February 7th.&lt;br /&gt;
(&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.americancinematheque.com/series/sunday-restorations/&quot;&gt;https://www.americancinematheque.com/series/sunday-restorations/&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;)&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3SkK38OMQF0&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3SkK38OMQF0&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy&amp;nbsp; the KPFK Film Club review here: https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3113203312288207&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;br /&gt;
Description: Kino Lorber repertory PRESENTS&amp;hellip; &amp;nbsp;The Olive Trees of Justice holds the dual distinction of being the only French film to have been shot during the Algerian War, and to have been the inaugural winner of the Critics Prize at the Cannes Film Festival in 1962. Filmed under the pretext that it was a documentary about the wine industry, the film depicts the Algerian struggle for independence from the French by concentrating on a young &amp;ldquo;pied-noir&amp;rdquo; (Frenchman of Algerian descent) who returns to Algiers to visit his dying father. His memories of boyhood on his father&amp;#39;s farm are told in flashbacks with a lush serenity that contrasts to the teeming, tank-filled streets of contemporary Algiers. Giving the film a neorealist tone by shooting in a documentary style and enrolling a cast that consisted largely of non-professional actors, Blue tells a powerful story of common people living and struggling in their daily lives while providing a valuable testimony to the complexity of the Algerian situation in that time period. Directed by James Blue, based on the novel by Jean P&amp;eacute;l&amp;eacute;gri. Winner: Critics Prize &amp;ndash; Cannes Film Festival (1962), Official Selection &amp;ndash; New York Film Festival (1963) &amp;quot;Lush, Lyrical... Stunningly Evocative&amp;quot;&amp;ndash;The New York Times.&lt;/p&gt;

