Description: A WINDOW INTO THE POETIC, PROGRESSIVE AND COMPLEX WORLD OF NEWARK&amp;rsquo;S BARAKA FAMILY. From the Newark Rebellion of 1967 to current day, the city&amp;rsquo;s narrative has been one of revolution with each generation picking up where the previous had left off. WHY IS WE AMERICANS? weighs in on Newark&amp;rsquo;s struggle against oppression through the personal triumphs and tragedies of the Baraka family -- from Amiri&amp;rsquo;s civil rights leadership and ultimate artistic marginalization, to the horrific murder of his sister, Kimako, through the homicide of daughter Shani (one of the first openly gay black activists) to the historic election of Ras Baraka as mayor of Newark, NJ.&lt;/p&gt;

