Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PkZwEmq60ZE&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PkZwEmq60ZE&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3074893516119187&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3074893516119187&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: CHILE&amp;rsquo;S OFFICIAL OSCAR&amp;reg; SUBMISSION FOR INTERNATIONAL FEATURE FILM. &amp;nbsp;Outsider Pictures is proud to announce the U.S. theatrical release of White on White (Blanco en blanco) the second feature by director Th&amp;eacute;o Court, winner of the Best Director and FIPRESCI Award in the Orizzonti competition at the Venice Film Festival. Set at the dawn of the twentieth century in Tierra del Fuego, a violent and hostile territory at the tip of Argentina where the continent meets the Straits of Magellan, White on White follows Pedro&amp;mdash;played by Alfredo Castro, seen in many of Pablo Larra&amp;iacute;n&amp;#39;s Chilean films, and star of From Afar and Rojo amongst many others&amp;mdash;a middle aged photographer who arrives to take wedding portraits of Miss Sara (Esther Vega), the soon to be child-bride of the powerful landowner Mr. Porter (Lars Rudolph). Fascinated by the young girl&amp;#39;s beauty he betrays the rules and becomes entrapped in the unsettled territory as a complicit witness to the genocide of the Selknam indigenous people.&amp;nbsp; With an impressive cast and an elegant cinematography, White on White is a poignant slow-burn neo-western that delves on the dire effects of colonialism and the casual violence of its photographic representation.&lt;/p&gt;

