Opens Dec. 3 at Cinema Village in New York, the Laemmle Glendale Cinema in L.A. (&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.laemmle.com/film/sleeping-negro&quot;&gt;https://www.laemmle.com/film/sleeping-negro&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;) and the Plaza Cinema in Atlanta, before getting a wider theatrical release and a digital and home-video release.&lt;br /&gt;
Get more info at the film&amp;rsquo;s website:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://artmattanfilms.com/the-sleeping-negro&quot;&gt;https://artmattanfilms.com/the-sleeping-negro&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://vimeo.com/577324000&quot;&gt;https://vimeo.com/577324000&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3067255716882967&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3067255716882967&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: ArtMattan Films presents a social justice drama by award-winning filmmaker Skinner Myers. &amp;nbsp;THE SLEEPING NEGRO opens with James Baldwin&amp;rsquo;s quote &amp;ldquo;To be a Negro in this country and to be relatively conscious is to be in rage almost all the time.&amp;rdquo; &amp;nbsp;It tells the story of a young Black man, simply identified as &amp;ldquo;Man,&amp;rdquo; who must resolve the personal meaning of his blackness when his white boss orders him to commit fraud to benefit the corporation. Struggling with an overwhelming sense of shame for going through with the illegal demand, Man seeks consolation by discussing his unease with a black former friend and his white fianc&amp;eacute;. &amp;nbsp;This does not go well.&amp;nbsp; &amp;ldquo;Following in the footsteps of the L.A. Rebellion filmmakers, Skinner Myers tells a very personal and intimate story in a radically non-traditional cinematic style as a means to express freely his feelings as a Black man in America.&amp;rdquo; says Dr. Reinaldo B. Spech, Principal at ArtMattan Films. He continues: &amp;ldquo;We are delighted to get behind this amazing independent production and all that it represents. &amp;nbsp;It is completely in line with our own vision as independent film distributors spotlighting the human experience of people of color all over the world. &amp;nbsp;This film is unapologetic, powerful and, in my view, a meaningful and relevant film about the African-American experience that should be seen by everyone.&amp;rdquo;&amp;nbsp; &amp;quot;A superb character study of a black man, how he sees himself and how he was treated by society, it is surreal yet real and terrifying.&amp;quot; ~ Ulkar Alakbarova, moviemovesme.com&lt;/p&gt;

