Description: A First-of-its-Kind Look at the Life of One of Cuba&amp;#39;s Biggest Stars and Last Grand Dames. &amp;nbsp;Coinciding with the 25th anniversary of the recording of the landmark Cuban album &amp;ldquo;Buena Vista Social Club,&amp;rdquo; Cuban-American director Hugo Perez is set to premiere his latest feature documentary Omara on the life of Afro-Cuban singer and cultural icon Omara Portuondo in the Sonic Cinema section at the 12th edition of DOC NYC, taking place in-person and online from November 11-18, 2021. Notably, Perez will also have a second title in its world premiere at this year&amp;rsquo;s festival, the documentary Once Upon a Time in Uganda, co-directed with Cathryne Czubek. An intimate portrait of one of Cuba&amp;rsquo;s most adored national treasures produced by Dana Kuznetzkoff and Frida Torresblanco, Omara offers unprecedented access to the legendary &amp;quot;Bride of Feeling,&amp;quot; often described as Cuba&amp;rsquo;s own Billie Holiday, to tell the story of Omara&amp;rsquo;s illustrious, seven decades-long career for the first time. Although Wim Wenders acclaimed and popular documentary Buena Vista Social Club beautifully captured the moment when Omara Portuondo was &amp;ldquo;rediscovered&amp;rdquo; by the world, her story goes much deeper. If you&amp;rsquo;ve heard the music of Buena Vista Social Club, then you&amp;rsquo;ve heard the unforgettable voice of Omara. At 90, Cuba&amp;#39;s legendary diva has been a driving force in Afro-Cuban music for over half a century. In the face of racism, misogyny, revolution and political controversies, Omara has used her music to connect with fans around the world in profound and sometimes unexpected ways, transcending borders while celebrating the soul of her beloved Cuba. In 2019, Omara was awarded a Latin Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award for her contributions to Latin American and world music. With intimate, unprecedented access to Omara Portuondo, audiences are invited to dive into her music and her life, and to explore how this Cuban girl-next-door came to resonate with so many people in so many disparate countries and cultures around the world.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;PENNEBAKER SERIES FILIBUSTER (PART TWO OF THE HEGEDUS AND PENNEBAKER&amp;rsquo;S EPIC SERIES THE ENERGY WAR) TO PREMIERE, FULLY RESTORED, AT DOC NYC&lt;br /&gt;
Info and tickets available at the DOC NYC website: &amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.docnyc.net/film/the-energy-war-filibuster/&quot;&gt;https://www.docnyc.net/film/the-energy-war-filibuster/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: PENNEBAKER HEGEDUS FILMS AND FOOTHILL PRODUCTIONS PARTNER TO PRESERVE THE WORK OF TWO INFLUENTIAL DOCUMENTARY FILMMAKERS. &amp;nbsp;Long before documentary series were the trend, filmmakers D.A. Pennebaker and Chris Hegedus created The Energy War, a ground-breaking episodic look at Washington, D.C in 1977-78. &amp;nbsp;Part Two of the series, &amp;ldquo;Filibuster,&amp;rdquo; is a real-life political drama, taking audiences behind-the-scenes during the fierce legislative battle and historic double filibuster over President Carter&amp;rsquo;s natural gas bill. Referred to as a &amp;ldquo;holy war,&amp;rdquo; the issue had evaded solutions for more than thirty years and six presidents. &amp;nbsp;The Energy War features combatants on all sides of the political aisle, from oil lobbyists to Senator Edward Kennedy to Secretary of Energy James R. Schlesinger. First aired on PBS in 1979, the series has scarcely been seen since. &amp;nbsp;The documentary continues to resonate today as politicians struggle to fix our current energy crisis. &amp;nbsp;The screening will take place on Saturday, November 13 at 2:15pm and features a conversation with filmmaker Chris Hegedus, along with film subjects, Barry Direnfeld and Thomas Susman who were legal counsel for Senators who mounted the filibuster, Senator Howard Metzenbaum and Senator Edward Kennedy, respectively.&lt;/p&gt;

