&lt;p&gt;MASS&lt;br /&gt;
Opens 10/22 at Selected Theaters. &amp;nbsp;Visit the film&amp;rsquo;s official Bleecker Street website for screening and other info:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://bleeckerstreetmedia.com/mass&quot;&gt;https://bleeckerstreetmedia.com/mass&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oU56Ns1nXsE&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oU56Ns1nXsE&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: &amp;ldquo;One of the most powerful films you&amp;rsquo;ll see in a long time.&amp;rdquo;&amp;mdash;KPFK Film Club. &amp;ldquo;An out-of-nowhere triumph, &amp;#39;Mass&amp;#39; is the sort of American drama that you rarely see anymore.&amp;rdquo;&amp;mdash; Matt Zoller Seitz, RogerEbert.com. &amp;nbsp; Years after an unspeakable tragedy tore their lives apart, two sets of parents (Jason Isaacs and Martha Plimpton, Reed Birney and Ann Dowd) agree to talk privately in an attempt to move forward. In Fran Kranz&amp;#39; writing and directing debut, he thoughtfully examines their journey of grief, anger and acceptance by coming face-to-face with the ones who have been left behind. &amp;nbsp;Special Note from the KPFK Film Club:&amp;nbsp;MASS is one of the most powerful films you&amp;rsquo;ll see in a long time. &amp;nbsp;The four leads offer Oscar worthy gut-wrenching performances, surrounded by an authentic supporting cast. &amp;nbsp;Although MASS has many of the hallmarks of a moving stage play, it equally has the characteristics of a gripping therapeutic encounter. &amp;nbsp;Two sets of parents (the parents of a school-shooter and the parents of a victim) meet in the basement of an Episcopalian Church to deal with their losses years after the violent episode that took both their sons&amp;rsquo; lives. &amp;nbsp;At first, they go through awkward pleasantries, which are followed by messy attempts to define what each person hopes to accomplish. &amp;nbsp;Ostensibly, the goal is healing, but there are hidden agendas, such as recrimination and revenge, defense and excuses. &amp;nbsp;Through the brave process of revealing deeply personal feelings and experiences, a kind of tentative bond, understanding, catharsis, and even acceptance is eventually forged that paves the way to the possibility of letting go (of grief) and moving on. With an emotive, thought-provoking script, the story that unfolds is an emotional roller coaster, with the potential to leave you both speechless and in tears, and then wanting share what you just experienced with someone you care about. &amp;nbsp;That experience might include anger, empathy, sorrow, outrage, horror, healing, etc. &amp;nbsp;But whatever the takeaway, this is searing drama that is bound to make you feel. &amp;nbsp;This makes MASS is an important, not-to-be-missed experience&lt;/p&gt;

