More info to come at the Greenwich website:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://greenwichentertainment.com/&quot;&gt;https://greenwichentertainment.com/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mfat4pSle6E&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mfat4pSle6E&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3016388125303060&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3016388125303060&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: GREENWICH ENTERTAINMENT presents&amp;hellip;Director Patrick Trefz&amp;rsquo;s MAN IN THE FIELD. The film profiles pioneering artist and chef Jim Denevan, founder of Outstanding in the Field, a radical alternative to the conventional dining experience. &amp;nbsp;The documentary intimately reveals Denevan&amp;rsquo;s artistic and culinary gifts with land art in epic geometric formations alongside grand dinners in beautiful natural settings. &amp;nbsp;Instead of bringing the food to the restaurant, Outstanding in the Field has brought the restaurant to the food since 1999. Hosted at one long table, with 100 to 1000 guests dining together, Denevan has set tables in vineyards, beaches, meadows, fishing docks, and city streets. &amp;nbsp;Over 120,000 lucky patrons in all 50 states and 16 countries have experienced this once-in-a-lifetime event and now Trefz&amp;rsquo;s film will allow audiences to experience it too.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;FIRE MUSIC&lt;br /&gt;
Opens in Los Angeles on Friday, Sept. 17 at the Laemmle Glendale (&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.laemmle.com/film/fire-music&quot;&gt;https://www.laemmle.com/film/fire-music&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;) following its release at New York&amp;rsquo;s Film Forum on September 10, with a national release to follow.&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3011731855768687&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3011731855768687&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Description:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;An Electrifying Freeform Tribute to the Free Jazz Revolution. &amp;nbsp;Submarine Deluxe is pleased to present the theatrical release of FIRE MUSIC, filmmaker and musician Tom Surgal&amp;rsquo;s documentary on the astonishing sounds (and sights) of the free jazz movement. Counting musicians Nels Cline and Thurston Moore are among its executive producers. &amp;nbsp;Although the free jazz movement of the 1960s and &amp;lsquo;70s was much maligned in some jazz circles, its pioneers &amp;ndash; brilliant talents like Ornette Coleman, Cecil Taylor, Sun Ra, Albert Ayler, and John Coltrane &amp;ndash; are today acknowledged as central to the evolution of jazz as America&amp;rsquo;s most innovative art form. &amp;nbsp;FIRE MUSIC showcases the architects of a movement whose radical brand of improvisation pushed harmonic and rhythmic boundaries and produced landmark albums like Coleman&amp;rsquo;s Free Jazz: A Collective Inspiration and Coltrane&amp;rsquo;s Ascension. A rich trove of archival footage conjures the 1960s jazz scene along with incisive reflections by critic Gary Giddins and a number of the movement&amp;rsquo;s key players.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;499&lt;br /&gt;
Opens on Friday, August 20 at BAM Rose Cinemas in New York City, followed by runs at the Laemmle Theaters in Los Angeles, and the Roxie Theater in San Francisco, before continuing on to a national rollout.&lt;br /&gt;
For more information, visit 499&amp;rsquo;s &amp;nbsp;Cinema Guild website:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.cinemaguild.com/theatrical/499.html&quot;&gt;http://www.cinemaguild.com/theatrical/499.html&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x7wzk64&quot;&gt;https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x7wzk64&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2991575057784367&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2991575057784367&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: Cinema Guild is proud to present the U.S. theatrical release of the fourth feature film by Mexican-American director Rodrigo Reyes. &amp;nbsp;499 reflects on the 500-year anniversary of the Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire in 2021, offering a bold hybrid cinema experience exploring the brutal legacy of colonialism in contemporary Mexico. Through the eyes of a ghostly conquistador (played by newcomer Eduardo San Juan Bre&amp;ntilde;a), Reyes recreates Hern&amp;aacute;n Cort&amp;eacute;s&amp;rsquo; epic journey from the coasts of Veracruz to the Aztec capital of Tenochtitlan, the site of contemporary Mexico City. &amp;nbsp;As the anachronistic fictional character interacts with real victims and subjects of Mexico&amp;rsquo;s failed drug wars, the filmmaker portrays the country&amp;rsquo;s current humanitarian crisis as part of a vicious and unfinished colonial project, still in motion, nearly five-hundred years later. Provocative, unique, and strikingly cinematic, 499 mixes non-fictional and performative elements with elements of the road movie to show how past traumas continue to affect contemporary reality. &amp;nbsp;While linking these seemingly disparate histories of violence, the film confirms Reyes as one of the most potent voices in American independent cinema. The filmmaking team has organized a Mexican tour for 499 following Cort&amp;eacute;s&amp;rsquo; original route from Veracruz to present-day Mexico City, taking place from July 31 to August 11. &amp;nbsp;The program will visit towns along the conquistador&amp;rsquo;s path, hosting special screenings of the film alongside conversations on the history of Mexico and the ongoing social problems that each community has faced in the aftermath of colonization.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;LAST NIGHT IN ROZZIE&lt;br /&gt;
Directed by Sean Gannet, starring Neil Brown Jr., Nicky Whelan, and Jeremy Sisto.&lt;br /&gt;
In Theaters and On VOD September 17th&lt;br /&gt;
Get more info from the film&amp;rsquo;s website:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.lastnightinrozzie.com/&quot;&gt;https://www.lastnightinrozzie.com/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qH0JnPPy3MM&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qH0JnPPy3MM&lt;/a&gt;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3012957345646138&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/&lt;wbr /&gt;permalink.php?story_fbid=&lt;wbr /&gt;3012957345646138&amp;amp;id=&lt;wbr /&gt;1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: GRAVITAS VENTURES PRESENTS AN ACCLAIMED STORY OF REDEMPTION!&amp;nbsp; &amp;ldquo;Complete and artfully defined characters... outstanding performances.&amp;rdquo;&amp;ndash; Peter Keough, author and Boston Globe film columnist. &amp;nbsp;A tale of self-reflection and the importance of facing trauma, LAST NIGHT IN ROZZIE is a testament to the importance of confronting your past. Ronnie Russo (Neil Brown Jr, STRAIGHT OUTTA COMPTON), a successful lawyer in New York, is summoned back to his old Boston neighborhood, Roslindale, by his childhood best friend Joey Donovan (Jeremy Sisto, SIX FEET UNDER). Now on his deathbed, Joey has only one request for Ronnie -help him reunite with his 10-year-old son. &amp;nbsp;Sympathetic to Joey&amp;#39;s situation, Ronnie works to get closer to Joey&amp;#39;s estranged ex-wife Pattie (Nicky Whelan, KNIGHT OF CUPS) to fulfill his friend&amp;#39;s dying wish. However, the more he learns about the man that Joey has become, the more he questions his mission. &amp;nbsp;Returning to his hometown after 25 years, Ronnie is forced to reconcile his traumatic past rooted in the last night he and Joey spent together as kids, and the repercussions that followed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;THE MEANING OF HITLER&lt;br /&gt;
IFC Films will release THE MEANING OF HITLER in theaters (including Laemmle&amp;rsquo;s Town Center 5 and Royal &amp;nbsp;at&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.laemmle.com/film/meaning-hitler&quot;&gt;https://www.laemmle.com/film/meaning-hitler&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;) and on-demand everywhere you can rent or buy movies on August 13th.&lt;br /&gt;
More info available at the IFC website:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.ifcfilms.com/films/the-meaning-of-hitler&quot;&gt;https://www.ifcfilms.com/films/the-meaning-of-hitler&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp; ;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2984984515110088&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2984984515110088&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: IFC Films Presents A &amp;ldquo;wise and original&amp;rdquo; reflection on history! Using the eponymous 1978 best-selling book as its frame, THE MEANING OF HITLER is a provocative interrogation of our culture&amp;rsquo;s fascination with Hitler and Nazism set against the backdrop of the current rise of white supremacy, the normalization of antisemitism and the weaponization of history itself. Shot in nine countries, the film traces Hitler&amp;rsquo;s movements, his rise to power and the scenes of his crimes as historians and writers, including Deborah Lipstadt, Martin Amis, Sir Richard Evans, Saul Friedlander, Yehuda Bauer, and famed Nazi hunters Beate and Serge Klarsfeld, weigh in on the lasting impact of his virulent ideology. &amp;nbsp;As fears of authoritarianism and fascism now abound, the film explores the myths and misconceptions of our understanding of the past and the difficult process of coming to terms with it at a time in our history when it seems more urgent than ever. The latest documentary from Petra Epperlein and Michael Tucker (Gunner Palace, Karl Marx City) inspired by Sebastian Haffner&amp;#39;s bestselling book, The Meaning of Hitler, explores a time in history that is constantly being challenged, denied and reframed making us draw parallels to the present.&lt;/p&gt;

