More info can be had at:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.musicboxfilms.com/film/mama-weed/&quot;&gt;https://www.musicboxfilms.com/film/mama-weed/&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2965207853754421&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2965207853754421&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: Brainstorm Media and Music Box Films are proud to announce the US theatrical release of MAMA WEED. A film by Jean-Paul Salom&amp;eacute;, Starring Isabelle Huppert!&amp;nbsp; A French-Arabic translator for the Paris police anti-narcotics unit, Patience Portefeux (Isabelle Huppert) interprets the daily calls and conversations between the city&amp;rsquo;s biggest drug dealers. &amp;nbsp;In the evenings, she looks in on her aging mother (Liliane Rov&amp;egrave;re, &amp;ldquo;Call My Agent&amp;rdquo;) at the long-term care facility where she is months behind in paying the bills. &amp;nbsp;When she overhears the son of one of her mother&amp;rsquo;s nurses on the wiretap, Patience is moved to protect him. &amp;nbsp;But her involvement in his business quickly escalates and she finds herself in possession of a huge store of hash and the insider knowledge required to move it. With her newly adopted retired police dog at her side, Patience transforms into Mama Weed, a savvy saleswoman capitalizing on her field experience to earn the extra income she so desperately needs while doing her best to stay one step ahead of her colleagues at the precinct. Based on &amp;quot;The Godmother,&amp;quot; the acclaimed novel by Hannelore Cayre, and nominated for a Best Adapted Screenplay C&amp;eacute;sar Award, MAMA WEED is a clever French crime caper featuring an impeccably charming performance from the legendary Isabelle Huppert.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;POV ANNOUNCES ITS LINEUP FOR THE 34TH SEASON!!&lt;br /&gt;
Premiering July 5 on PBS, with a Prominent Latin American and U.S. Latinx selection making up more than half of this year&amp;rsquo;s programming, POV (&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.pbs.org/pov/&quot;&gt;https://www.pbs.org/pov/&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;) marks a historic moment for Latinx narrative representation on PBS and public television more broadly. &amp;nbsp;America&amp;rsquo;s longest-running documentary series will host the broadcast premiere of seven powerful and critically-acclaimed Latin American and U.S. Latinx Documentaries:&amp;nbsp;LANDFALL, STATELESS (Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2965657493709457&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2965657493709457&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;)&amp;nbsp;THE SONG OF BUTTERFLIES, FRUITS OF LABOR, THINGS WE DARE NOT DO, LA CASA DE MAMA ICHA, and ON THE DIVIDE&lt;br /&gt;
Description: POV&amp;rsquo;s newest season follows artists, activists, elders, comedians, frontline workers and politicians across the globe as they navigate their personal stories and the larger histories under which they take shape. &amp;nbsp;All films are accompanied by educational resources and will be available to stream on all PBS platforms including PBS.org, and the PBS Video App. Premieres continue through fall 2021 with primetime specials in early 2022. &amp;nbsp;Additional titles, including the fourth season of POV Shorts and streaming and interactive projects, will be announced throughout the year.&lt;br /&gt;
POV Season 34 Schedule:&lt;br /&gt;
--THE NEUTRAL GROUND, directed by CJ Hunt, July 5, 2021. &amp;nbsp;CJ Hunt investigates why a losing army from 1865 still holds so much power in America.&lt;br /&gt;
--LANDFALL, directed by Cecilia Aldarondo, July 12, 2021. &amp;nbsp;Shard-like glimpses of post-Hurricane Mar&amp;iacute;a Puerto Rico examine a transformed world.&lt;br /&gt;
--STATELESS, directed by Mich&amp;egrave;le Stephenson, July 19, 2021. &amp;nbsp;An attorney advocates for Dominicans of Haitain descent who have been stripped of their citizenship.&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2965657493709457&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2965657493709457&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
--MAYOR, directed by David Osit, July 26, 2021. &amp;nbsp;Musa Hadid is the mayor of Ramallah, the de facto capital of Palestine. Winner Grand Jury Award Full Frame Documentary Film Festival.&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2816835318591676&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2816835318591676&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
--PIER&amp;nbsp;KIDS, directed by Elegance Bratton, August 2, 2021. &amp;nbsp;In New York City, queer and trans youth of color make the Christopher Street Pier their own.&lt;br /&gt;
--THE SONG OF THE BUTTERFLIES, directed by N&amp;uacute;ria Frigola Torrent, August 30, 2021. &amp;nbsp;Rember, an Indigenous artist in Peru, journeys home to the Amazonian land of his ancestors.&lt;br /&gt;
--FRUITS OF LABOR, directed by Emily Cohen Iba&amp;ntilde;ez, October 4, 2021. &amp;nbsp;In central California, a Mexican-American teen goes to work when ICE raids threaten her family.&lt;br /&gt;
--LA CASA DE MAMA ICHA, directed by Oscar Molina, October 18, 2021. &amp;nbsp;Mama Icha returns home to Colombia, finding heartbreak and joy after decades in the U.S.&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review at:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=3037036746571531&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/&lt;wbr /&gt;permalink.php?story_fbid=&lt;wbr /&gt;3037036746571531&amp;amp;id=&lt;wbr /&gt;1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
--THINGS WE DARE NOT DO, directed by Bruno Santamar&amp;iacute;a, October 25, 2021. &amp;nbsp;In a Mexican coastal village, 16-year-old &amp;Ntilde;o&amp;ntilde;o has a secret that defies gender norms.&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/1718261665115719/photos/a.1718312808443938/2775678882707320/?type=3&amp;amp;theater&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/1718261665115719/photos/a.1718312808443938/2775678882707320/?type=3&amp;amp;theater&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
--NORTH BY CURRENT, directed by Angelo Madsen Minax, November 1, 2021. &amp;nbsp;Director Angelo Madsen Minax returns home to rural Michigan after the death of his niece.&lt;br /&gt;
--UNAPOLOGETIC, directed by Ashley O&amp;rsquo;Shay, December 27, 2021. &amp;nbsp;After two police killings, Black abolitionists fight to hold Chicago officials accountable.&lt;br /&gt;
--NOT GOING QUIETLY, directed by Nicholas Bruckman, January 24, 2022. &amp;nbsp;After being diagnosed with ALS, Ady Barkan launches a national movement for healthcare.&lt;br /&gt;
--ON THE DIVIDE, directed by Maya Cueva and Leah Galant, Spring 2022. &amp;nbsp;The lives of three Latinx people intersect at the last abortion clinic on the border.&lt;br /&gt;
Broadcast on the national PBS schedule, POV is available to millions of viewers on-air, online and in communities. To support educators and parents tackling remote learning, POV will produce educational resources for every episode, including lesson plans, discussion guides and reading lists with several materials available in Spanish.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;WHO WILL START ANOTHER FIRE&lt;br /&gt;
The new 9 film anthology launches June 11 in select theaters nationwide, virtual cinemas (including the Laemmle Theaters) through KinoMarquee.com, on VOD at KinoNow.com and with a limited-edition DVD release available at KinoLorber.com. There is a Charles Burnett introduction to the inaugural collection available as a bonus feature on the dvd. &amp;nbsp;Select in-person screenings will also take place across the nation with independent theaters that are open.&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JXOlP5NL3z8&amp;amp;feature=emb_logo&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JXOlP5NL3z8&amp;amp;feature=emb_logo&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2942370286038178&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2942370286038178&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: Kino Lorber and Dedza Films are announcing their first collaborative release of WHO WILL START ANOTHER FIRE, an international short film omnibus showcasing the works of nine emerging filmmakers from underrepresented communities around the world. Official selections for WHO WILL START ANOTHER FIRE:&lt;br /&gt;
LIKE FLYING--A young Chinese-American girl navigates her childhood through her parents&amp;rsquo; broken relationship.&lt;br /&gt;
FAMILY TREE--Nagawa, an 8 year old schoolgirl, is presenting a school project about her family tree to her classmates and teacher. When her mother Margaret picks up Nagawa from school, she doesn&amp;#39;t have the heart to tell her daughter that her beloved father has been in a terrible accident.&lt;br /&gt;
TROUBLEMAKER--Obi is hot, bored, and desperate for something to do. When his best friend, Emeka, gives him a packet of firecrackers, the boys decide to have some fun.&lt;br /&gt;
POLYGRAPH--Based on a true story, Yasmine, an openly lesbian Arab nurse living in Tel Aviv, finds out that her lover Or, an intelligence officer in the Israeli army, has been reporting on their relationship.&lt;br /&gt;
THE LIGHTS ARE ON, NO ONE&amp;rsquo;S HOME--Mar, a trans woman who left home years ago, returns to her old neighborhood to find her childhood home. Upon her return, she&amp;rsquo;s confronted with the changes that gentrification has brought to the place she once knew so well.&lt;br /&gt;
BY WAY OF CANARSIE--A wandering portrait of an oft-neglected shoreline community, By Way of Canarsie imagines possible futures at odds with a peaceful present. The competing futures for Canarsie Pier present complications about how and for whom this public space serves.&lt;br /&gt;
THE ROSE OF MANILA--An imagining of the formative years of Imelda Marcos, who, as one half of the Marcos regime, would become infamous for embezzling billions from the country to sustain her extravagant lifestyle. Here, the fate of a young girl and an entire nation become entangled as the absent mother of a country is born.&lt;br /&gt;
SLIP--A woman arrives home at the end of a regular day, but as she begins to turn in for the night, she is overcome with a sense of restlessness. Unable to fit inside her own world, she goes back out into the night.&lt;br /&gt;
NOT BLACK ENOUGH--A young African-American man struggling to find his identity within his community meets a persuasive relic of the past. Featuring Corey Knight (We Are Who We Are) and Patrick Decile (Moonlight).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;TRUMAN &amp;amp; TENNESSEE: AN INTIMATE CONVERSATION&lt;br /&gt;
OPENING JUNE 18: In New York at the Film Forum, In Los Angeles at The Nuart, and Laemmle Playhouse &amp;amp; Town Center 5; Also available in virtual cinemas nationwide through KinoMarquee.com &amp;nbsp;(&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.kinolorber.com/film/view/id/4728&quot;&gt;https://www.kinolorber.com/film/view/id/4728&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;)&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=epUZZheLXuA&amp;amp;t=11s&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=epUZZheLXuA&amp;amp;t=11s&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here: https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2948762315398975&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;br /&gt;
Description: A REVELATORY LOOK AT THE LIFELONG FRIENDSHIP BETWEEN LEGENDARY WRITERS TRUMAN CAPOTE &amp;amp; TENNESSEE WILLIAMS... Filmmaker Lisa Immordino Vreeland masterfully collages a wealth of archival material, including dishy talk show appearances with Dick Cavett and David Frost, with clips from some of the duo&amp;rsquo;s most memorable movie adaptions: A STREETCAR NAMED DESIRE, CAT ON A HOT TIN ROOF, THE GLASS MENAGERIE, BREAKFAST AT TIFFANY&amp;rsquo;S, and IN COLD BLOOD. Featuring vibrant voiceover work by award-winning actors Jim Parsons (Capote) and Zachary Quinto (Williams), the film is dripping with wit and wisdom. It is a celebration of both men&amp;#39;s fearless candor and often tumultuous friendship that honors how their identity as gay Southerners informed their timeless artistic achievements and relationships with family, colleagues, confidants, and &amp;ndash; most significantly &amp;ndash; each other. OFFICIAL SELECTION at the Telluride Film Festival, Hamptons International Film Festival, NewFest, and the Seattle International Film Festival, Full Frame, Frameline. &amp;ldquo;A truly captivating and cleverly contrasting examination of two of the most significant writers of the last century.&amp;rdquo;-- Frank J. Avella, Edge Media. &amp;ldquo;A visually appealing mosaic of iconic photographs, television interviews, magazine articles, clippings and comments that combine to fully immerse us in the lives and loves of both men.&amp;rdquo;-- Allan Hunter, Screen International&lt;/p&gt;

