Description: A virtual screening of the multi-award-winning documentary AND Q&amp;amp;A&amp;hellip;watch the film online first and then join the discussion! Rabbi Joachim Prinz, a refugee from Nazi Germany came to the United States in 1937 and immediately identified with African-Americans experiencing the same kinds of oppression he had known as a Jew in Hitler&amp;#39;s Germany. Working with Martin Luther King, Prinz became a prominent leader of the civil rights movement in the US, culminating in his stirring speech at the 1963 March on Washington, when he cautioned, &amp;quot;America must not become a nation of onlookers. . . . America must not remain silent!&amp;quot; This documentary uncovers the dramatic story of a courageous religious leader whose passion for justice compelled him to speak out against bigotry over the course of five decades.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;PERFUME DE GARDENIAS&lt;br /&gt;
A World Premiere at the 2021 Tribeca Film Festival June 9 to 20.&lt;br /&gt;
Info and tickets available here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://tribecafilm.com/films/perfume-de-gardenias-2021&quot;&gt;https://tribecafilm.com/films/perfume-de-gardenias-2021&lt;/a&gt;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2945746172367256&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2945746172367256&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: A Provocative Reflection on Death and Mourning Featuring Veteran Actress Luz Mar&amp;iacute;a Rond&amp;oacute;n in Her First Movie-Starring Role. The Debut Feature by Queer Afro-Puerto Rican Multidisciplinary Artist Macha Col&amp;oacute;n Offers a Playful and Darkly Comic Perspective on Puerto Rico. A dark comedy that captures the idiosyncrasies and spirit of a nation adept at creating novel strategies for laughter in the face of adversity, the film tells the story of Isabel (Luz Mar&amp;iacute;a Rond&amp;oacute;n), an elderly woman living in a middle-class neighborhood in Puerto Rico, who has just become a widow after having cared for her husband until his last breaths. However, her recent loss becomes a blessing when she crafts a beautiful custom-made funeral for him that catches the attention of To&amp;ntilde;a (Sharon Riley), a pious but domineering woman who involves herself in local funerals. To&amp;ntilde;a is the self-appointed leader of a coterie of church ladies elderly, and she enlists Isabel to put her unusual talents to good use and design custom, idiosyncratic funerals for her ailing neighbors. As Isabel agrees to perform this peculiar line of work&amp;mdash;offering seniors a chance to dictate how their lives should be honored, before they die&amp;mdash;she also finds renewed purpose in her own life. Along the way, however, Isabel is forced to question her own beliefs, as well as her relationship with both life and death. Perfume de Gardenias brings the daring, cheerful, and radically &amp;ldquo;cuir&amp;rdquo; style that characterizes Macha Col&amp;oacute;n&amp;rsquo;s artistic output to the silver screen, capturing the vivid colors of the Caribbean island by offering a nuanced portrait of the customs, characters, and idiosyncrasies of its battered middle class.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;THROUGH THE NIGHT&amp;nbsp;by Afro-Dominican Filmmaker Loira Limbal,&lt;br /&gt;
Debuts May 10 on PBS at 10 p.m. ET (check local listings) and at pov.org; The film will also be available to stream for free at pov.org until June 10, 2021.&lt;br /&gt;
Get more info here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.amdoc.org/watch/throughthenight/&quot;&gt;https://www.amdoc.org/watch/throughthenight/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Play the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tXx4mM0hHEA&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tXx4mM0hHEA&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2921252111483329&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/&lt;wbr /&gt;permalink.php?story_fbid=&lt;wbr /&gt;2921252111483329&amp;amp;id=&lt;wbr /&gt;1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: POV Presents the National Broadcast Premiere. A Timely Portrait of Resilience, Love, and the Fundamental Role of Caregivers from Afro-Dominican Filmmaker Loira Limbal. An official selection at the 2020 Tribeca Film Festival as well as at DOC NYC and AFI DOCS, Through the Night is an intimate cinema verit&amp;eacute; portrait of three working mothers whose lives intersect at a 24-hour daycare center in New Rochelle, New York: a mother working the overnight shift as an essential worker at a pediatric hospital; another holding down three jobs in order to support her family, and a woman who, for over two decades, has cared for the children whose parents have nowhere else to turn. Through the Night showcases the multiplicity of &amp;ldquo;women&amp;rsquo;s work&amp;rdquo; &amp;mdash; paid, underpaid, and unpaid; emotional and physical; domestic and career-oriented &amp;mdash; all while negotiating the terms of a dignified existence under the three arrows of racism, sexism, and capitalism in America. In the wake of the COVID-19 pandemic, Through the Night and the stories it centers take on an even greater sense of urgency and profound meaning.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;TWO GODS&lt;br /&gt;
In Theaters and Virtual Cinemas &amp;nbsp;(including the Laemmle Theaters:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.laemmle.com/film/two-gods&quot;&gt;https://www.laemmle.com/film/two-gods&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;) on Friday, May 21&lt;br /&gt;
More info available at:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://twogodsfilm.com/&quot;&gt;https://twogodsfilm.com/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Trailer:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://youtu.be/NYWTAPahnZU&quot;&gt;https://youtu.be/NYWTAPahnZU&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2931579260450614&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/&lt;wbr /&gt;permalink.php?story_fbid=&lt;wbr /&gt;2931579260450614&amp;amp;id=&lt;wbr /&gt;1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: A Powerful Story of Brotherhood and Redemption. In an area of Newark where too many funerals commemorate tragically short lives, Hanif, an older man with a troubled past, works as a casket maker and ritual body washer. He is committed to his work and to his Islamic faith and is also a dedicated mentor to two local kids&amp;mdash;Furquan, a confident 12-year-old who comes from a rough home and Naz, a 17-year-old who has been fighting through his own struggles as a young Black man growing up in Newark. Challenges come when Furquan&amp;#39;s home life becomes more turbulent and Naz gets caught up in a serious arrest. Hanif, struggling with the fear that he has failed as a mentor, begins to fall into a downward spiral. Zeshawn Ali&amp;rsquo;s TWO GODS is the beautifully observed story of a Black Muslim casket maker in Newark, New Jersey, who takes two vulnerable young men from his community under his wing. A festival standout since it world-premiered at the Hot Docs Film Festival, the film has since shown at the Full Frame, DOC NYC, Camden, New Orleans (Jury Award), Montclair (Jury Award), and Florida (Jury Award) festivals, among others. Shot in exquisite black and white, Zeshawn Ali&amp;rsquo;s auspicious feature debut is a lyrical meditation on the importance of community and passing down generational knowledge through faith, brotherhood and redemption. &amp;ldquo;A timely portrait of lives lost and redeemed.&amp;rdquo; - Jordan Mintzer, The Hollywood Reporter. &amp;ldquo;An auspicious debut&amp;hellip; a poetic meditation on life, death and the struggle to survive in between.&amp;rdquo; - Lauren Wissot, Filmmaker Magazine. &amp;quot;A masterpiece just waiting to be discovered.&amp;rdquo; - Joshua Brunsting, CriterionCast.&lt;/p&gt;

