Enjoy the trailer here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=El4-2zrNppA&amp;amp;t=22s&quot;&gt;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=El4-2zrNppA&amp;amp;t=22s&lt;/a&gt;;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2935179393423934&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2935179393423934&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: A reworking of the ancient myth of the mysterious water spirit in the modern world. Set in Berlin, UNDINE works as a historian lecturing on Berlin&amp;rsquo;s urban development. She knows all about the Humboldt Forum, and has a knack for dressing. She is nonchalantly beautiful, and the way she imparts her knowledge about the city that was built on a swamp is as professional as it is graceful. But Undine&amp;rsquo;s world collapses when the man she loves leaves her. Soon the ancient myth catches up with her and Undine has to kill the man who betrays her and return to the water. UNDINE is the story of a life-or-death love, splendidly and effortlessly told. Esteemed German director Christian Petzold returns for his ninth feature with UNDINE, a modern interpretation of the titular myth. Reuniting his charismatic TRANSIT stars, Paula Beer and Franz Rogowski, Petzold paints a heartfelt love story which blossoms through the pair&amp;#39;s radiant chemistry. In a fluid blend of fantasy and reality, we watch a creature of legend defy destiny and attempt to re-interpret the bounds of her mythos through a contemporary lens. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;Few male directors of Petzold&amp;rsquo;s stature have committed themselves so deeply to women-centric narratives.&amp;rdquo; - Variety, Peter Debruge. &amp;ldquo;An odd new beauty from one of Germany&amp;rsquo;s best directors.&amp;rdquo; - The Hollywood Reporter, Boyd van Hoeij. &amp;ldquo;Simultaneously baffling and completely lucid. A head scratcher and a soul shaker.&amp;rdquo; - Little White Lies, David Jenkins. Written and directed by Christian Petzold (BARBARA, PHOENIX, TRANSIT); starring Paula Beer (NEVER LOOK AWAY) &amp;amp; Franz Rogowski (TRANSIT)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;BILL TRAYLOR: CHASING GHOSTS&lt;br /&gt;
Opens Friday, April 16 &amp;nbsp;In Theaters at New York&amp;#39;s Film Forum &amp;amp; Los Angeles&amp;#39; Laemmle NoHo 7 (tickets and info here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.laemmle.com/film/bill-traylor-chasing-ghosts&quot;&gt;https://www.laemmle.com/film/bill-traylor-chasing-ghosts&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;)&lt;br /&gt;
Also available in virtual theaters across U.S. through Kino Marquee:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://kinomarquee.com/film/venue/604f8e7e9392d90001c8a93a&quot;&gt;https://kinomarquee.com/film/venue/604f8e7e9392d90001c8a93a&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2904327499842457&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2904327499842457&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Description: The revealing documentary about the pioneering art sensation who was born into slavery...whose works became an art sensation! This illuminating documentary explores the life of a unique American artist, a man with a remarkable and unlikely biography. Bill Traylor was born into slavery in 1853 on a cotton plantation in rural Alabama. After the Civil War, Traylor continued to farm the land as a sharecropper until the late 1920s. Aging and alone, he moved to Montgomery and worked odd jobs in the thriving segregated black neighborhood. A decade later, in his late 80s, Traylor became homeless and started to draw and paint, both memories from plantation days and scenes of a radically changing urban culture. &amp;nbsp;Having witnessed profound social and political change during a life spanning slavery, Reconstruction, Jim Crow segregation, and the Great Migration, Traylor devised his own visual language to translate an oral culture into something original, powerful, and culturally rooted. He made well over a thousand drawings and paintings between 1939-1942. This colorful, strikingly modernist work eventually led him to be recognized as one of America&amp;rsquo;s greatest self-taught artists and the subject of a Smithsonian retrospective. Using historical and cultural context, Bill Traylor: Chasing Ghosts brings the spirit and mystery of Traylor&amp;rsquo;s incomparable art to life. Making dramatic and surprising use of tap dance and evocative period music, the film balances archival photographs and footage, insightful perspectives from his descendents, and Traylor&amp;rsquo;s striking drawings and paintings to reveal one of America&amp;rsquo;s most prominent artists to a wide audience.&lt;/p&gt;

