January 8&lt;br /&gt;
THE REASON I JUMP, Directed by Jerry Rothwell&lt;br /&gt;
Enjoy the KPFK Film Club Review here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=2831579600450581&amp;amp;id=1718261665115719&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/&lt;wbr /&gt;permalink.php?story_fbid=&lt;wbr /&gt;2831579600450581&amp;amp;id=&lt;wbr /&gt;1718261665115719&amp;nbsp;&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;quot;This is a wondrous work... that enlightens and informs but that is also ravishing to behold.&amp;quot; -- The Hollywood Reporter;&amp;nbsp; Winner: Audience Award, World Documentary &amp;ndash; Sundance Film Festival&lt;br /&gt;
Nominee: Best Feature, Best Director &amp;ndash; IDA Documentary Awards&lt;br /&gt;
Nominee: Best Cinematography &amp;ndash; Critics Choice Documentary Awards&lt;br /&gt;
Based on the best-selling book by Naoki Higashida, The Reason I Jump is an immersive cinematic exploration of neurodiversity through the experiences of nonspeaking autistic people from around the world. The film blends Higashida&amp;#39;s revelatory insights into autism, written when he was just 13, with intimate portraits of five remarkable young people. It opens a window for audiences into an intense and overwhelming, but often joyful, sensory universe.&lt;br /&gt;
Moments in the lives of each of the characters are linked by the journey of a young Japanese boy through an epic landscape; narrated passages from Naoki&amp;rsquo;s writing reflect on what his autism means to him and others, how his perception of the world differs, and why he acts in the way he does: the reason he jumps. The film distils these elements into a sensually rich tapestry that leads us to Naoki&amp;rsquo;s core message: not being able to speak does not mean there is nothing to say.&lt;br /&gt;
