&lt;b&gt;Description:&lt;/b&gt; The First Entirely Oil-Painted Feature Film, Comes to The Frida November 24th &amp;ndash; 30th.&amp;nbsp; Already the winner of four international awards, Loving Vincent takes a revolutionary approach in relating the last days of famed artist Vincent Van Gogh, as each of the film&amp;rsquo;s 65,000 frames is an oil painting on canvas, created in the same technique as Van Gogh by a team of 115 painters.&amp;nbsp; A true first-of-its-kind film that mesmerizes from start to finish, Loving Vincent explores the life and unusual death of Van Gogh via depictions of his artworks, and seen through the eyes of a young man who arrives in the painter&amp;rsquo;s hometown to deliver the troubled artist&amp;rsquo;s final letter, and who ends up investigating his final days there. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;One of the most lunatic labors of love to appear on movie screens this year. And in that sense, a fitting, miraculous tribute to its subject.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; Joe McGovern, Entertainment Weekly. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;An engrossing exploration of the artist&amp;rsquo;s final days rendered in his signature painting style.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; Serena Donadoni, Village Voice. &amp;ldquo;Loving Vincent is almost too beautiful for its own good; I found myself, too often, so dazzled by the form that I quite forgot about the content.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; Moira MacDonald, Seattle Times. &amp;ldquo;Brings a poetic sense of tragedy to the last act of van Gogh&amp;rsquo;s life, and fresh insight into the kind of man he was.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; Peter Debruge, Variety&lt;br /&gt;
