&lt;strong style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px; border:0px; outline:0px; font-size:12px; background:transparent&quot;&gt;Description:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;border:0px; font-size:12px; margin:0px; padding:0px&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background:transparent&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;outline:0px&quot;&gt;YOU ARE INVITED to attend one of LA&amp;rsquo;s PREMIERE Film Events&amp;hellip; The 20th Annual ARPA international Film Festival, &amp;nbsp;a diverse range of feature films, riveting documentaries, and thought-provoking shorts.&amp;nbsp; Of course you&amp;rsquo;ll want to attend the SPECIAL EVENTS, such as Friday&amp;rsquo;s Red Carpet with Reception &amp;amp; Entertainment (before and after the Opening Night Program), Saturday&amp;rsquo;s Centerpiece Programs and Receptions (with food, wine, and entertainment), illuminating Q and A&amp;rsquo;s with Filmmakers, and Sunday&amp;rsquo;s Closing Night Awards Gala Banquet, featuring special performances by theremin virtuoso Armen Ra and renowned vocalist Mister X.&amp;nbsp; The Awards Gala on November 5 at Loews Hollywood Hotel will honor Oscar-winning director/screenwriter Terry George, actor Carl Weathers, Oscar-winning screenwriter Alexander Dinelaris and pay a special tribute to the late music icon Chris Cornell. &amp;nbsp;Film highlights include Friday&amp;rsquo;s story of acclaimed music icon DALIDA, one of the most modern, liberated, and talented women of the 20th century.&amp;nbsp; DALIDA&amp;nbsp; is an intimate portrait based on the real story of a strong, fiercely independent international acting and singing sensation whose 30-year dazzling career was punctuated by tragic events. Saturday&amp;rsquo;s Centerpiece Documentary INTENT TO DESTROY pulls back the curtain of political resistance and historical amnesia to finally present a more complete account of Armenia &amp;ndash;the Genocide, its delayed recognition and a nearly forgotten history of suffering and heroism in the hope of inspiring a collective sense of international justice and humanity. Saturday&amp;rsquo;s Feature Film PINSKY is a comedy nominated for Best Screenplay, Best Director and Best Feature Film.&amp;nbsp; In the wake of a bad breakup and the death of her grandfather, Sophia Pinsky moves back home under the martial law of her Russian grandmother and is forced to reevaluate the terms of her adult life&amp;hellip; PINSKY is about finding your chosen family and forgiving the one you&amp;#39;re born into. Other highlights include APRICOT GROVES (a drama featuring LGBT themes) , Krasny (a &amp;rdquo;red&amp;rdquo; western set in the south of post revolutionary Russia), and Sunday&amp;rsquo;s documentary THE HEART OF NUBA (&amp;ldquo;One doctor, one hospital, one million patients&amp;rsquo;&amp;hellip;a &amp;nbsp;doctor selflessly and courageously serves the needs of a forgotten people as the region is bombed relentlessly by an indicted war criminal.)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

