&lt;strong style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px; border:0px; outline:0px; font-size:12px; background:transparent&quot;&gt;Description:&lt;/strong&gt;VARIETE, the 1925 German Silent Classic that had the whole world talking back in 1925, will be screening &amp;nbsp;on 8/12 at 2PM at the most wondrous Cinefamily Theater on Fairfax!!!&amp;nbsp; And to top it off, the amazing Cliff Retallick will provide live musical accompaniment!!! (review and interview with Mr. Retallick here:&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.facebook.com/1718261665115719/photos/a.1718312808443938.1073741828.1718261665115719/1928879404053943/?type=3&amp;amp;theater&quot; style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px; border:0px; outline:none; font-size:12px; background:transparent; text-decoration:none&quot;&gt;https://www.facebook.com/1718261665115719/photos/a.1718312808443938.1073741828.1718261665115719/1928879404053943/?type=3&amp;amp;theater&lt;/a&gt;) Set in the wild and extravagant world of carnivals, circuses and variety performances, VARIETE had cinematography with flair and a camera that flipped and spun with the acrobats. &amp;nbsp;It was also a tale of infidelity, jealousy and murder, all shown in detail. &amp;nbsp;Adapted from a 1921 novel by Felix Hollaender, Variete is a gem extracted from the golden age of twenties German silent film. The film follows a trapeze artist &amp;ndash; accompanied by &amp;ldquo;unleashed&amp;rdquo; acrobatic camera work to match. Presented in a new DCP restoration! &amp;ldquo;This is a production which not only shows the way in which a story should be unfurled, but impresses one with the magic of the camera in picturing effects, such as the torrent of thoughts rushing through a maddened mind, and the views of the audience from the eyes of a hurtling trapeze performer.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; Mordaunt Hall, The New York Times.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;