&lt;strong style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px; border:0px; outline:0px; font-size:12px; background:transparent&quot;&gt;Description:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;The Cinefamily Proudly Presents Eric Rohmer&amp;rsquo;s Fascinating SIX MORAL TALES. Based on a collection of short stories that Rohmer had written in his twenties, the SIX MORAL TALES vaulted Rohmer to international fame and commercial success! Each of the Tales concerns a man&amp;rsquo;s fascination with a woman as a digression in the man&amp;rsquo;s life; he eventually returns, &amp;nbsp;with little or no regret, to life with another woman, the man&amp;rsquo;s true partner.&amp;nbsp; In each, the protagonist&amp;rsquo;s version of the story is different from the audience&amp;rsquo;s version, with supporting players in one version the leads in the other. The French word &amp;quot;moraliste&amp;quot; does not translate to the English word &amp;quot;moral&amp;quot; and has more to do with what someone thinks and feels. Thus the films can be seen as investigations about what characters think about their behavior rather than about the behavior itself.&amp;nbsp; Rohmer has said that he wanted to portray in film what seemed most alien to the medium, to express feelings buried deep in our consciousness.&amp;nbsp; The SIX MORAL TALES unleashed onto the film world a new voice&amp;mdash;sexy, philosophical, modern, daring, nonjudgmental, and liberating. And the results helped establish Rohmer as one of the most acclaimed directors of the famous French New Wave. Six Titles on Five Screening Dates:&lt;br style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px&quot; /&gt;
&lt;strong style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px; border:0px; outline:0px; font-size:12px; background:transparent&quot;&gt;The Bakery Girl of Monceau &amp;amp; Suzanne&amp;rsquo;s Career&lt;/strong&gt;--In the first of Rohmer&amp;rsquo;s &amp;ldquo;Moral Tales,&amp;rdquo; a law student (Barbet Schroeder) with a roving eye and a large appetite stuffs himself full of sugar cookies and pastries daily in order to garner the attentions of the pretty brunette who works in a quaint Paris bakery. In Suzanne&amp;rsquo;s Career, Bertrand bides his time in a casually hostile and envious friendship with college chum Guillaume. But when ladies&amp;rsquo; man Guillaume seems to be making a play for the spirited, independent Suzanne, Bertrand watches bitterly with disapproval and jealousy.&lt;br style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px&quot; /&gt;
&lt;strong style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px; border:0px; outline:0px; font-size:12px; background:transparent&quot;&gt;My Night at Maud&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/strong&gt;-- In the brilliantly accomplished centerpiece of Rohmer&amp;rsquo;s &amp;ldquo;Moral Tales&amp;rdquo; series, Jean-Louis Trintignant plays Jean-Louis, a pious Catholic engineer who unwittingly spends the night at the apartment of the bold, brunette divorc&amp;eacute;e Maud, where his rigid ethical standards are challenged.&amp;nbsp; Oscar nominated and Cannes Award Winner.&lt;br style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px&quot; /&gt;
&lt;strong style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px; border:0px; outline:0px; font-size:12px; background:transparent&quot;&gt;La Collectionneuse&lt;/strong&gt;- -In Rohmer&amp;rsquo;s first color film, a bombastic, womanizing art dealer and his painter friend go to a seventeenth-century villa on the Riviera for a relaxing summer getaway. But their idyll is disturbed by the presence of the bohemian Hayd&amp;eacute;e, accused of being a &amp;ldquo;collector&amp;rdquo; of men.&lt;br style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px&quot; /&gt;
&lt;strong style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px; border:0px; outline:0px; font-size:12px; background:transparent&quot;&gt;Claire&amp;#39;s Knee&lt;/strong&gt;--&amp;ldquo;Why would I tie myself to one woman if I were interested in others?&amp;rdquo; says Jer&amp;ocirc;me, even as he plans on marrying a diplomat&amp;rsquo;s daughter by summer&amp;rsquo;s end. Before then, Jer&amp;ocirc;me spends his July at a lakeside boardinghouse nursing crushes on the sixteen-year-old Laura and her blonde stepsister, Claire.&lt;br style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px&quot; /&gt;
&lt;strong style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px; border:0px; outline:0px; font-size:12px; background:transparent&quot;&gt;Love in the Afternoon&lt;/strong&gt;--In the luminous final chapter to Rohmer&amp;rsquo;s &amp;ldquo;Moral Tales,&amp;rdquo; the bourgeois business executive Fr&amp;eacute;d&amp;eacute;ric, though happily married to an adoring wife, cannot banish from his mind the multitude of attractive Parisian women who pass him every day. Then arrives Chlo&amp;eacute;, an audacious, unencumbered old flame.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

