&lt;strong style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px; border:0px; outline:0px; font-size:12px; background:transparent&quot;&gt;Description:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;Silent film fans, the time has come to rejoice! Now on the second Saturday of every month, get ready to receive The Silent Treatment:&amp;nbsp; Cinefamily&amp;rsquo;s ongoing series of artfully chosen feature films from all corners of the pre-sound era &amp;mdash; choice picks that are rarely screened theatrically, or are not available on DVD!&amp;nbsp; On July 8th at 2PM the Cinefamily screens EVE&amp;rsquo;S LEAVES with live accompaniment by Cliff Retallick!!! Based on the play by Harry Chapman Ford and directed by Paul Sloane, the film follows a sea captain who forces his daughter Eve (Leatrice Joy) to masquerade as a boy. Eve responds by provoking widespread mischief aboard her father&amp;rsquo;s tramp freighter (ironically named &amp;ldquo;The Garden of Eden&amp;rdquo;). While the plot is laden with melodrama, it is comedy that forms the true heart of this movie.&amp;nbsp; William Boyd, who would later achieve greater fame as cowboy hero Hopalong Cassidy, is commendable as the object of Eve&amp;rsquo;s desire; but while their combined screen chemistry is palpable (as witnessed in the truly memorable &amp;ldquo;apple-kissing&amp;rdquo; scene), it is Joy&amp;rsquo;s ebullient performance that ultimately steals the show.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

