&lt;strong style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px; border:0px; outline:0px; font-size:12px; background:transparent&quot;&gt;Description&lt;/strong&gt;: Which French film has been hailed by critics as the greatest movie of all time? If you guessed Jean Vigo&amp;rsquo;s L&amp;#39;Atalante, you&amp;rsquo;re right! This1934 romance is an obsessively precise masterpiece, anchored by a deep reverence for the cinematic craft, enriched by dynamic camera work, jaw-dropping visuals, and a sense of playfulness. A captain of a river barge marries a local village girl and they decide to live on the barge, along with the ship&amp;rsquo;s crew.&amp;nbsp; What starts as a makeshift romantic river trip to Paris becomes a tempestuous honeymoon. L&amp;rsquo;Atalante is a profoundly moving love story, a fascinating tale of two newlyweds which is full of magic and beauty.&amp;nbsp; Co-presented by the French Film and TV Office&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

