&lt;strong style=&quot;margin:0px; padding:0px; border:0px; outline:0px; font-size:12px; background:transparent&quot;&gt;DESCRIPTION:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;In Maura Axelrod&amp;#39;s iconoclastic documentary, we meet the art world&amp;rsquo;s enfant terrible Maurizio Cattelan, one of the most successful&amp;mdash;and controversial&amp;mdash;artists of our time. His work is designed to offend and insult&amp;mdash;and yet, the more he abuses people, it seems the more popular he becomes according to one observer. The film documents Maurizio from his early days in poverty to his recent career-capping retrospective at the Guggenheim, with a few twists along the way. Axelrod&amp;#39;s playful profile leaves no stone unturned in trying to figure out: Who is Maurizio Cattelan?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

