&lt;b style=&quot;box-sizing:inherit; font-weight:bold&quot;&gt;Description:&lt;/b&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Tim Robbins said it best at the 1997 Academy Awards, &amp;ldquo;Ladies and Gentlemen, the best neighbor any of us have ever had, Fred Rogers!&amp;rdquo; For over thirty years, Fred Rogers, an unassuming minister, puppeteer, writer and producer was beamed daily into homes across America. &amp;nbsp;In his beloved television program, Mister Rogers&amp;rsquo; Neighborhood, Fred and his cast of puppets and friends spoke directly to young children about some of life&amp;rsquo;s weightiest issues, in a simple, direct fashion. &amp;nbsp;There hadn&amp;rsquo;t been anything like Mr. Rogers on television before and there hasn&amp;rsquo;t been since. Though he may be best known today as a soft-spoken, cardigan-wearing children&amp;rsquo;s television host, in reality, Fred Rogers&amp;rsquo; career represents a sustained attempt to present a coherent, beneficent view about how we should best speak to children about important matters. &amp;nbsp;A portrait of a man whom we all think we know, this emotional and moving film takes us and into the heart of a creative genius who inspired generations of children with compassion and limitless imagination. From Academy Award&amp;reg;-winning filmmaker Morgan Neville (20 Feet from Stardom, The Music of Strangers, The Best of Enemies.) &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;Both nostalgic and immediate, it&amp;rsquo;s a documentary you want to hug.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; Hollywood Reporter. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;This beautiful film celebrates a deeply good man with a great gift for repairing.&amp;rdquo; --Wall Street Journal &amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br style=&quot;box-sizing:inherit&quot; /&gt;
