&lt;b style=&quot;box-sizing:inherit; font-weight:bold&quot;&gt;Description:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br style=&quot;box-sizing:inherit&quot; /&gt;
&lt;b style=&quot;box-sizing:inherit; font-weight:bold&quot;&gt;THE ROOM:&lt;/b&gt;&amp;nbsp;Bust out those plastic spoons! &amp;nbsp;Tommy Wiseau&amp;rsquo;s THE ROOM returns to The Frida Cinema every last Saturday of the month through 2018!! &amp;nbsp;Tommy Wiseau&amp;rsquo;s peerless magnum opus finds the auteur who shaped a generation taking on the arts of acting, writing, casting, directing, editing and more. What&amp;rsquo;s even more remarkable: he&amp;rsquo;s mastered them all. In Wiseau&amp;rsquo;s The Room, Johnny is a big-time banker working in gorgeously shot San Francisco. His fianc&amp;eacute; Lisa, seemingly a happy part of a successful relationship, has wandering eyes&amp;hellip;for Tommy&amp;rsquo;s best friend Mark. Cinema has never witnessed such betrayal!! The Room is an intense, sensual thriller punctuated with brilliant musical contributions by Mladen Milicevic, Jarah Gibson, Clint Gamboa, Kitra Williams &amp;amp; Reflection. Wiseau&amp;rsquo;s intricately knit web of sweet secrets and bitter lies interrogates the very form of drama itself, abandoning a slick and finished aesthetic to showcase his inventive and creative spirit. Especially notable is Wiseau&amp;rsquo;s masterful naturalistic acting. Join us and witness a master at work. This is truly unforgettable cinema.&lt;br style=&quot;box-sizing:inherit&quot; /&gt;
&lt;b style=&quot;box-sizing:inherit; font-weight:bold&quot;&gt;The DISASTER ARTIST&lt;/b&gt;: Cinematic irony: when a film about what might be the Worst Film Ever Made ends up being one of the most critically-acclaimed films of the year, and a five-time Best Actor Winner and seven-time Best Screenplay Winner (so far). In director James Franco&amp;rsquo;s The Disaster Artist, Franco himself stars as Tommy Wiseau, writer-producer-director of the 2003 cult-classic disasterpiece The Room. &amp;nbsp;Based on Greg Sestero&amp;rsquo;s best-selling tell-all about the making of The Room, The Disaster Artist avoids the trappings of being simply a hit-piece on its notoriously bizarre subject filmmaker by emerging as a celebration of artistic expression, friendship, and dreams pursued against insurmountable odds, elevated by screenwriters Scott Neustadter and Michael H. Weber&amp;rsquo;s alternately hilarious and poignant script. &amp;nbsp;Led by an invested performance by Franco who all but transforms himself into Wiseau, The Disaster Artist is a portrait of a man whose passion was as sincere as his methods were questionable, and is a hilarious and welcome reminder that there is more than one way to become a legend&amp;mdash;and no limit to what you can achieve when you have absolutely no idea what you&amp;rsquo;re doing. &amp;ldquo;Funny &amp;mdash; sometimes brutally &amp;mdash; and surprisingly touching, it works whether you&amp;rsquo;ve seen the source material or not, though there are plentiful shout-outs to die-hard fans.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; Sarah Stewart, New York Post. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;Grade: 4/4. The Disaster Artist is funny from the beginning &amp;ndash; but it becomes downright side-splitting once Tommy gets onto a film set.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; Mick LaSalle, San Francisco Chronicle. &amp;nbsp;&amp;ldquo;James Franco is firing on all his creative cylinders in this comic bonanza about Tommy Wiseau, the worst filmmaker of the 21st century. Franco hits a new career peak by making sure his film is as heartfelt as it is hilarious.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash; Peter Travers, Rolling Stone&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

